  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Torkelson single walks off White Sox in Ten Innings",
    "subheadline": "Dramatic Finish in the 10th Innings Lifts Detroit Tigers",
    "lead_angle": "Spencer Torkelson slapped a single past a drawn-in infield, pushing the winning run across in the tenth inning and delivering the Detroit Tigers a 5-4 victory over the Chicago White Sox. The knock capped a frantic final frame at Comerica Park. The Tigers trailed by a run entering the bottom half but rallied for two against reliever Brandon Eisert, who was saddled with the loss. Will Vest, who recorded the final out in the top of the inning, picked up the win.\n\nChicago looked to have the game sealed, carrying a two-run lead into the eighth. But the Tigers refused to go quietly. They scraped a run across in the eighth and then knotted the score with two outs in the bottom of the ninth, forcing the extra frame. The late rally erased an earlier push from the White Sox, who had taken the lead on a two-run home run by Luisangel Acuña in the sixth inning.\n\nTorkelson anchored the Detroit attack, finishing 2-for-4 with the game-ending run batted in. His final swing was the most important, but it was part of a persistent effort that saw him and Riley Greene each collect a pair of hits. The victory pulls the Tigers closer to Chicago in a tight divisional race. For the White Sox, the loss stings, wasting a two-hit, two-RBI day from Tristan Peters.",
    "reason": "Extra-inning walk-off — the purest combination of tension and resolution the sport offers."
  },
